Earlier this week, I had the opportunity to hear an extremely charismatic Marine General speak about his vision for the future. He was captivating. As I thought more over his message though, I felt it was not fully based on the reality of current operations. Normally, that’s not a big deal because usually a vision exceeds the bounds of current reality; however, where a vision exceeds reality, the leader must be willing to make the decisions and take the actions necessary to keep the vision aloft. I feel the General’s vision won’t take flight because the big machine is unwilling to make the changes necessary to accomplish it.
.
So if you’re a leader, a true visionary, understand the current state of affairs, and lead the way through decision and action to keep the foundation of your vision strong.
#leadership #development #vision #leader #amimakingsense

FEUILLARD EXERCISE POST 2/2 - NO. 34
i believe this exercise is slightly easier than no.33 as the initial melody isn’t remotely as overwhelming to play through. 
this exercise claims to focus on ‘developing suppleness of the wrist’ but i believe it helps develop so much more than just that! while 33 focused much more on the fingering hand, rhythm and strength/control of the bow, 34 is much more beneficial in developing bow control and utilising the entire bow hair when playing. you can see the same bow markings underneath each variation indicating where to start from or how much bow to use - again helping develop control and awareness of how much bow you actually use when you play. 
the different note values in each variation also helps train you to make fuller use of the bow as if you use a full bow for a longer note, you can obviously take more time, whereas if it’s a shorter note and you have to use the same amount of bow, you have less time to do so. with practice, this will train you to use whole bows and achieve a fuller sound much more frequently when performing pieces. 
as well as developing strength in the bowing hand when using different sections of the bow, the different note values help develop wrist flexibility and articulation. for example, as the note values get shorter throughout the variations, flexibility of the wrist becomes more important for articulating the notes and producing a pleasant sound when playing shorter notes, so practicing these variations help develop that flexibility. 
finally, another bowing technique in these variations that help improve articulation and bow control is the slurred shorter notes towards the end of the exercise, this helps improve at string crossing and is therefore useful for focusing on an even sound for each note. 
this concludes my two posts on technique! i hope it all makes sense to you string players and has helped or at least been interesting to find out so many benefits! everything in this post as well as the last is my own opinion based on what i’ve noticed when practicing these exercises, if you have anything to add to what i’ve said about them don’t hesitate to...

FEUILLARD EXERCISE POST 1/2 - NO. 33
this exercise is brilliant in so many ways. you can see pictured the original melody and the full list of variations so that you can visualise the examples i’ve played or even practice them all yourself if you like! i typically play through the whole melody with all 33 variations in one practice (and then usually all of exercise 34 too) because it really helps warm up my fingers and the elbow and shoulder of my bowing arm. 
in the photo you may notice the markings underneath each variation, these indicate where to start on the bow and how much of the bow to use, so: G = whole bow, H = half bow, Fr = start at heel/frog of bow, Sp = start at tip of bow, M = start in middle of bow. this is great for developing bow control (e.g. if you’re making full use of the bow hair or if you’re able to use specific sections of the bow efficiently). it’s also very useful for developing strength in the wrist and index finger of your bowing hand, for example it’s much harder to produce a strong sound or maintain the overall sound at the tip of the bow, so practicing the variations focusing on the tip and frog can really help pay attention to a full sound and improve strength to achieve it. 
the different rhythms featured in the variations also help in many ways. even just running through the original melody of constant semiquavers can help warm up the fingers so that they are less rigid/stiff, more flexible and faster moving. the majority of variations feature the same rhythm until no.23, this new rhythm helps prepare your fingers to perform the melody in a different style to how it is originally written. i also believe practicing these different rhythms can help train your mind to switch between rhythms more efficiently in general which can aid sightreading pieces as well as improving your general sense of rhythm. it wouldn’t seem like it but often changing the rhythm of particular phrases in pieces can help improve your tuning and training your fingers to know exactly where to go next, i often do this for phrases that are particularly fast so that i...
